entry.title: Roll src/third_party/boringssl/src 23824fa0f..4fe29ebc7
entry.content:
https://boringssl.googlesource.com/boringssl/+log/23824fa0fed94f4660ffafb15aaea8b317f2c8a6..4fe29ebc759e482891e96fc4170eb3db26c0bc13



The following commits have Chromium bugs associated:

9a4e1095c Remove redundant bssl_sys import



The following commits have update notes:

90f0f05cc Integrate TLS 1.2 sigalg and cipher suite selection

da3b3725a Don't report libpki headers as part of libcrypto



This required a couple fixes to tests:



First, SSLPolicyTest.InsecureHashPolicy forgot to disable non-ECDHE

ciphers, which meant the server could have chosen to fallback to a

non-signing cipher. It just happened not to, but 90f0f05cc fixed this.



Second, 90f0f05cc slightly tweaks the error reporting for signature

algorithm mismatch. Previously, we would select a cipher suite and only

notice the failure condition at ServerKeyExchange. This means the client

sees ServerHello, Certificate, handshake_failure. Now we notice the

errro condition early and don't waste our time sending ServerHello and

Certificate. The peer simply sees handshake_failure. It's the same

alert, but Chrome maps this earlier handshake_failure to a different

error. (This mapping is more accurate because there wasn't a protocol

mistake. We just didn't have common parameters.)

entry.title: [ios] Integrate account bookmarks consistently into omnibox
entry.content:
Before this patch, some but not all of omnibox code integrated

with the second existing instance of BookmarkModel on iOS,

AccountBookmarkModelFactory.



The most important callers, e.g. the omnibox's BookmarkProvider,

already integrated with all underlying BookmarkModel instances

before this patch. This means, for these cases, the patch is a pure

refactoring without behavioral changes.



In other cases, such as BookmarkScoringSignalsAnnotator, account

bookmarks were never implemented, presumably due to an oversight.

With this patch, this (minor) bug is fixed. The same is true for

HistoryProvider.



Outside iOS, the issue doesn't exist as there is a single

BookmarkModel instance.



The approach proposed here leans on the recently-introduced

BookmarkModelFactory on iOS, which will eventually replace the

other two factories. During the migration, the factory returns

CoreBookmarkModel, which is a subset of BookmarkModel, and an

API designed to behave identically on all platforms: if needed,

namely on iOS, it presents a merged view. The patch requires

extending CoreBookmarkModel to accommodate the needs that omnibox

has, following closely analogous APIs that already exist in

BookmarkModel.

entry.title: Remove separate suffix parsing and support new <ac> - <phone> rule.
entry.content:
The PhoneFieldParser::Parse searches for phone number fields based on

grammars. These grammars may contain FIELD_SUFFIX entries, which

corresponds to the zzz in a US phone number of format "(xxx) yyyy zzzz".

After processing all grammars, the function took another attempt at

discovering a phone suffix. This extra attempt succeeded in 0.03% of

phone number fields (i.e. 3 in 10.000). I tried incorpoating this as new

grammar rules but I am concerned about negative side effects. The only

rules that carried some traffic were:

- Area Code: Phone:

- Phone:



I have replaced suffix handling for the first rule with new grammars:

```

// Area Code: Phone: -

{{REGEX_AREA, FIELD_AREA_CODE},

{REGEX_PHONE, FIELD_PHONE},

{REGEX_SUFFIX_SEPARATOR, FIELD_SUFFIX}},

// Area Code: Phone: Suffix

{{REGEX_AREA, FIELD_AREA_CODE},

{REGEX_PHONE, FIELD_PHONE},

{REGEX_SUFFIX, FIELD_SUFFIX}},

```



I have not introduced a rule

```

// Phone: -

{{REGEX_PHONE, FIELD_PHONE}, {REGEX_SUFFIX_SEPARATOR, FIELD_SUFFIX}},

```

because I believe that such a construct should be interpreted as

```

// Phone: -

{{REGEX_PHONE, FIELD_AREA_CODE}, {REGEX_PREFIX_SEPARATOR, FIELD_PHONE}},

```



I am not rolling this out behind a finch gate because these rules trigger very

rarely. They don't trigger on my end-to-end tests.

entry.title: [anchor] Support non-lengths in anchor query fallbacks
entry.content:
CL:5285936 incorrectly changed CSSMathExpressionAnchorQuery to always

have category_=kCalcLength whenever CSSAnchorPositioningComputeAnchor

is enabled, but neglected to handle the cases where the fallback

value is either a or .



This CL sets the category to kCalcLength when we're sure that's

the case, otherwise kCalcPercentLength.



Our calc() machinery expects to be able to determine the category

of a given node "statically" (parse time), but anchor() violates this

since its category depends on the result of the query.

For example, for anchor(--a top, 10%), if this is a valid query

and we don't use the fallback (10%), then this should have behaved

as a kCalcLength all along, even if we had a percentage in the fallback.

Fixing this properly is a big project on its own, so for now we treat

any cases involving percent as kCalcPercentLength, and track any

serialization bugs that arise from that using chromium:326088870.

entry.title: Revert "Update last interacted form when JS modifies a field's value"
entry.content:
This reverts commit 05c6be3dfec78f091d537673fbf65605f7a41776.



Reason for revert: Speedometer2 regressions. I will reupload another CL

that tries to achieve the same result with possibly no regressions



Original change's description:

> Update last interacted form when JS modifies a field's value

>

> Autofill is currently working on replacing the observer it uses for

> disappearing elements by a direct blink connection notifying of removals

> and hiding of elements.

>

> Some notification about hidden elements are provided to Autofill during

> style recalc (e.g. changing visibility attribute to 'hidden') and during

> this Autofill is not allowed to query the focusability of a node.

>

> This causes a problem for Autofill: When submission is inferred,

> Autofill tries to extract the form of the element it was tracking, and

> part of this is querying the focusability of fields. Which means that

> if submission is inferred from a notification sent during style recalc,

> Autofill is not allowed to extract a form at submission time.

>

> The alternative is to use the provisionally saved form, which is a form

> that Autofill updates on autofill operations and user edits. In this

> context, form means either an HTML
tagged section or the

> collection of all unowned control elements.

>

> This CL tries to make the provisionally saved form approach the state of

> the extracted form at submission time (should we have extracted it)

> by also updating it on JS changes. To achieve that, we modify the signal

> JavaScriptModifiedAutofilledValue to JavaScriptModifiedValue.

>

> Note that this update is only performed if JS modifies the form that is

> already tracked by autofill. Which means that only user edits and

> autofill (also user triggered) have permission to change the form

> tracked by autofill from one form to another, but JS only has permission

> to update the currently tracked form.

>

> The CL also adds logic to default to the provisionally save form

> unconditionally at submission time instead of extraction.

>

> All behavior changes are gated behind a feature flag.

>

replaces weak_ptr with this in PowerManagerClientProxy.

Original change's description:

> Reland #2: "[A11y] Stable ids for AXObjects with DOM nodes"

>

> This is a reland of commit 01466963a42b3bd5fdbe5bc5ac17bff6304b058d

>

> The reland was reverted because TAST test inputs.VirtualKeyboardAccent still fails sometimes.

>

> Original change's description:

> > Reland: [A11y] Stable ids for AXObjects with DOM nodes

> >

> > Reland of CL:4027071. The revert was caused because of the breaking

> > of a TAST test. Basically, some code in AXTreeSerializer that deleted subtrees of old child ids is not triggered as often, because if the DOM node doesn't change, the child ID doesn't. That's a good thing usually, but if the node is reattached with new style, we need to make sure its children are reconsidered. The fix is that in the specific case where

> > a node is reattached, call ChildrenChanged() instead of just marking it dirty -- in AXObjectCacheImpl::UpdateCacheAfterNodeIsAttached().

> >

> > ----

> >

> > Use the DOM node for the AXID for any AXObject with a DOM node. Other AXObjects will still generate their AXID, but in their own numerical namespace. For now, any AXID < 0 will be a generated ID.

> >

> > Role changes and alerts required some new browser-side code, because rather than the object being destroyed and created with a new id, the ID now stays the same.

> >

> > In some cases, test results have improved, e.g. rather than an object being destroyed and created with a different ID, it retains the same ID and a change event is fired for it.

> >

> > Benefits:

> > - Removes over 100 lines of implementation code

> > - Use less memory: removes ids_in_use_ (set) and node_object_mapping_ (map).

> > - Reduce map lookups when an AXObject is removed -- based on the ID value, we can determine whether it has a DOM node and if it doesn't, we already know it cannot be in some of the maps

> > - Make it easier for screen readers to maintain the user's point of regard within content, even when the layout or role changes. Users sometimes lose their place, as the screen reader may move the user to the top. A hope is that this will reduce the occurrences of that happening. It may even be possible for screen readers to keep their place in tabs where the AX tree is released from memory and later regenerated, which could open up possibilities to using less memory.

> > Follow-up work:

> > - Refactor content-visibility: auto change handling in a11y (crbug.com/1380449).

> > - Look at simplifying or removing reparenting computations in AXTreeSerializer. Maybe we can get rid of expensive AnyDescendantIsReparented().

> > - Merge GetAXID() and GetExistingAXID() -- see TODO.

entry.title: DOM: Add iframe insertion & removal steps WPTs
entry.content:
To help resolve https://github.com/whatwg/dom/issues/808, we need WPTs

asserting exactly when (DOM-observing) script can and cannot be invoked

during the insertion and removing steps for iframes and script elements.



The tests in this CL assert the current spec behavior of:



Iframe:

- Insertion:

- Synchronously fire the `load` event in the iframe document

- Removal:

- No script is run in between multiple iframe removals. Script

cannot observe the state of the DOM in between multiple

synchronous removals because, i.e., no `unload` events are fired

in this case per HTML [1].

Script:

- Insertion:

- Synchronously execute

entry.title: [chromevox]: fixes potential CHECK in ~AccessibilityPanelWidgetObserver
entry.content:
The intent of the CHECK in ~AccessibilityPanelWidgetObserver is to

enforce that it no longer observes `widget_`.



This is ordinarily achieved in OnWidgetDestroying, but calls to

Widget::CloseNow

do not guarantee such calls on the same callstack.



In theory (and as shown in the bug), requests can come into

CreateChromeVoxPanel

in-between (and async tasks of)

Widget::CloseNow

and

OnWidgetDestroying



leading to the CHECK within

~AccessibilityPanelWidgetObserver

being triggered.



Fix this by also observing

OnWidgetClosing

which is called on the same call stack as

Widget::CloseNow.



R=katie@chromium.org

entry.title: Reland #2: "[A11y] Stable ids for AXObjects with DOM nodes"
entry.content:
This is a reland of commit 01466963a42b3bd5fdbe5bc5ac17bff6304b058d



The reland was reverted because TAST test inputs.VirtualKeyboardAccent still fails sometimes.



Original change's description:

> Reland: [A11y] Stable ids for AXObjects with DOM nodes

>

> Reland of CL:4027071. The revert was caused because of the breaking

> of a TAST test. Basically, some code in AXTreeSerializer that deleted subtrees of old child ids is not triggered as often, because if the DOM node doesn't change, the child ID doesn't. That's a good thing usually, but if the node is reattached with new style, we need to make sure its children are reconsidered. The fix is that in the specific case where

> a node is reattached, call ChildrenChanged() instead of just marking it dirty -- in AXObjectCacheImpl::UpdateCacheAfterNodeIsAttached().

>

> ----

>

> Use the DOM node for the AXID for any AXObject with a DOM node. Other AXObjects will still generate their AXID, but in their own numerical namespace. For now, any AXID < 0 will be a generated ID.

>

> Role changes and alerts required some new browser-side code, because rather than the object being destroyed and created with a new id, the ID now stays the same.

>

> In some cases, test results have improved, e.g. rather than an object being destroyed and created with a different ID, it retains the same ID and a change event is fired for it.

>

> Benefits:

> - Removes over 100 lines of implementation code

> - Use less memory: removes ids_in_use_ (set) and node_object_mapping_ (map).

> - Reduce map lookups when an AXObject is removed -- based on the ID value, we can determine whether it has a DOM node and if it doesn't, we already know it cannot be in some of the maps

> - Make it easier for screen readers to maintain the user's point of regard within content, even when the layout or role changes. Users sometimes lose their place, as the screen reader may move the user to the top. A hope is that this will reduce the occurrences of that happening. It may even be possible for screen readers to keep their place in tabs where the AX tree is released from memory and later regenerated, which could open up possibilities to using less memory.

> - Enable the follow-ups listed below.

>

> Follow-up work:

> - Refactor content-visibility: auto change handling in a11y (crbug.com/1380449).

> - See if the dom_node_id field in AXNodeData is needed anymore now that any id >0 is the same as the dom node id.

> - Look at simplifying or removing reparenting computations in AXTreeSerializer. Maybe we can get rid of expensive AnyDescendantIsReparented().

> - Merge GetAXID() and GetExistingAXID() -- see TODO.

>
